+{"id":"frankentorch-go4q","title":"tensor_renorm severs autograd; composable via permute/reshape/norm/clamp/div/mul","description":"tensor_renorm at lib.rs:15185 normalizes sub-tensors along a dim so their p-norm is bounded by maxnorm. The body extracts values, computes the per-slice norm in plain f64, conditionally scales, and rebuilds a non-grad leaf — silently severing autograd. PyTorch's torch.renorm IS differentiable (sub-gradient at the boundary norm == maxnorm).

Closed form for the scale factor:
   scale_d = maxnorm / max(norm_d, maxnorm)
which equals 1 when norm_d <= maxnorm and maxnorm/norm_d when norm_d > maxnorm.

Composable via:
   permute dim to position 0
   reshape to [dim_size, other_size]
   abs + pow + sum_dim(1) + pow(1/p)  → norm per slice
   denom = clamp_min(norm, maxnorm)
   scale = maxnorm / denom
   broadcast scale via unsqueeze + expand
   mul, reshape back, permute back

Used heavily in embedding regularization (torch.nn.Embedding(max_norm=...)). Surfaced during /reality-check pass.","notes":"Fixed in this commit. Composed tensor_renorm through permute/reshape/abs/pow/sum_dim/clamp_min/div/mul/expand. The closed-form scale per slice is maxnorm / max(norm, maxnorm), which equals 1 when norm <= maxnorm and maxnorm/norm when norm > maxnorm — clamp_min(norm, maxnorm) gives exactly the denom we want. Strategy: permute dim to position 0, reshape to [dim_size, other_size], compute per-row L_p norm, scale each row, reshape + permute back. dim==0 case skips the (no-op) permutes. Added renorm_propagates_gradient_through_input regression test (mixed clamp / no-clamp rows; row 1 in identity branch gives grad=1, row 0 in scaled branch gives finite non-zero). ft-api lib tests: 1166.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-30T22:20:36.063042844Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-30T22:23:02.572388294Z","closed_at":"2026-04-30T22:23:02.569085070Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
